1
00:00:01,330 --> 00:00:30,190
Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambuddhassa Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambuddhassa Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambuddhassa Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble,

2
00:00:30,524 --> 00:00:39,936
and fully self-awakened one.

3
00:00:44,783 --> 00:00:59,063
So first of all, many thanks to Donatella who is translating for me.

4
00:00:59,853 --> 00:01:25,724
honeying my words with her angelic voice so i'm going to give a talk on the um qualities of the buddha the nine qualities so this is what we chant when we do puja

5
00:01:26,498 --> 00:01:33,893
So this evening I will talk about the nine qualities of the Buddha, which we refer to when we listen to the Puja.

6
00:01:35,121 --> 00:02:00,775
So we chant that in the morning, eh?

7
00:02:01,496 --> 00:02:08,948
So the first quality is arahant.

8
00:02:10,409 --> 00:02:23,808
And it means accomplished, somebody who is worthy of respect.

9
00:02:25,290 --> 00:02:32,001
Now, what the commentators do is they begin to separate the word to give it more meaning.

10
00:02:33,162 --> 00:02:39,330
Quello che fanno i commentatori è separano la parola dandogli un significato più vasto.

11
00:02:40,393 --> 00:02:47,924
And the one that makes sense to me is the division between Ari and Hatta.

12
00:02:47,943 --> 00:02:52,850
La separazione che per me è più valida è quella tra Ari e Hatta.

13
00:02:53,894 --> 00:02:56,078
It means he destroyed his enemies.

14
00:03:01,508 --> 00:03:04,433
Now the enemies, of course, are the defilements.

15
00:03:05,956 --> 00:03:16,257
Now the defilements are listed as ten.

16
00:03:16,810 --> 00:03:25,425
But actually in the scriptures it just means anything that is unwholesome within our personality.

17
00:03:26,526 --> 00:03:40,590
And such a person has no secret evil.

18
00:03:41,481 --> 00:04:07,606
And he can say with the Buddha, with all the enlightened people, that birth is destroyed and the holy life has been lived.

19
00:04:08,481 --> 00:04:19,839
che la nascita è distrutta e la vita sacra è conseguita.

20
00:04:20,781 --> 00:04:23,666
What had to be done has been done.

21
00:04:24,848 --> 00:04:28,134
Ciò che doveva essere compiuto è stato compiuto.

22
00:04:29,396 --> 00:04:31,839
There is no more rebirth for me.

23
00:04:32,596 --> 00:04:42,754
So whenever we say Arahant, that's what we mean.

24
00:04:47,581 --> 00:04:52,730
Now the second one is Sammasambuddho, which means self-enlightened.

25
00:04:53,639 --> 00:05:13,807
So this is the crucial role that the first person plays for us.

26
00:05:15,322 --> 00:05:19,187
Somebody must have planted the first wheat.

27
00:05:20,507 --> 00:05:24,112
Qualcuno deve aver piantato the first wheat.

28
00:05:24,372 --> 00:05:25,853
What do you mean?

29
00:05:25,874 --> 00:05:26,375
Yeah, wheat.

30
00:05:28,396 --> 00:05:29,077
Yeah, grain.

31
00:05:29,637 --> 00:05:34,023
Qualcuno ha piantato il primo stelo di grano.

32
00:05:35,785 --> 00:05:38,187
Somebody must have created the wheel.

33
00:05:39,367 --> 00:05:43,692
Qualcuno deve avere creato la ruota.

34
00:05:44,247 --> 00:05:57,980
And we know that Edmund Hillary and Sherpa Tenzing climbed Everest.

35
00:05:59,622 --> 00:06:11,115
So once they did it, everybody else can do it, even the dogs.

36
00:06:11,651 --> 00:06:20,822
Ah, so in other words, the one who initiates, who begins something, has a special place within our praise.

37
00:06:22,062 --> 00:06:40,663
And so this means that the first person, the one who started all this, has a place, a special place in what we attribute to him, in the blessings we wish him.

38
00:06:41,572 --> 00:06:44,596
So he is the founder of our tradition.

39
00:06:46,158 --> 00:06:56,935
So without him there simply wouldn't be any Buddhism.

40
00:06:57,776 --> 00:07:03,985
Now the next quality is endowed with clear vision,

41
00:07:04,910 --> 00:07:23,028
or we can say direct understanding, and virtuous conduct.

42
00:07:27,471 --> 00:07:32,757
So this means that he has understood the cause of our problems,

43
00:07:33,682 --> 00:07:47,154
and of his own problems.

44
00:07:47,995 --> 00:07:51,738
And because of that, his actions are always virtuous.

45
00:07:53,680 --> 00:08:03,029
So remember that everything begins from this misunderstanding.

46
00:08:04,293 --> 00:08:13,846
It's a misunderstanding as to who we are.

47
00:08:14,927 --> 00:08:30,468
Presuming ourselves to be human beings, that's all, we seek happiness in the sensual world.

48
00:08:31,360 --> 00:08:58,717
And this creates what we call an attachment, which means we are dependent on the sensual world to make us happy.

49
00:08:59,542 --> 00:09:10,514
And this leads us to certain unfortunate qualities.

50
00:09:12,577 --> 00:09:25,633
Greed, aversion and fear.

51
00:09:25,697 --> 00:09:30,806
Ah, and all the rest.

52
00:09:31,648 --> 00:09:33,250
All the rest of human misery.

53
00:09:34,231 --> 00:09:52,160
So, in other words, he is somebody who has understood the path and understands it to be a path of purification.

54
00:09:52,410 --> 00:10:09,001
The next quality is translated as someone who has completed a journey.

55
00:10:10,078 --> 00:10:39,427
So this includes all the training that he went to with his two teachers, and his own discovery of the path,

56
00:10:40,167 --> 00:11:00,302
And don't forget that he also did some very severe mortification exercises.

57
00:11:00,990 --> 00:11:22,500
So in other words, by practicing in the wrong paths, he eventually found the right path.

58
00:11:24,784 --> 00:11:26,187
So this often happens to us.

59
00:11:26,407 --> 00:11:29,951
First you make mistakes and then you find the right way to do something.

60
00:11:30,639 --> 00:11:44,996
Now, the next one is a seer of the worlds.

61
00:11:45,538 --> 00:12:00,174
Now, this does not refer specifically to seeing other realms of being.

62
00:12:00,879 --> 00:12:19,302
This is to do with the worlds that we create.

63
00:12:21,104 --> 00:12:27,511
These are the ones that we manufacture our little universes.

64
00:12:28,386 --> 00:12:50,638
So sometimes we're in the hell realm, when we're depressed and upset.

65
00:12:52,720 --> 00:12:57,567
Sometimes we were in the animal realm, when we used to get drunk, but we don't do that anymore.

66
00:12:58,407 --> 00:13:11,803
And then there's the hungry ghost realm when we are very greedy.

67
00:13:12,924 --> 00:13:28,144
And sometimes we're in the human realm where we have some sort of intelligence, some sort of wisdom.

68
00:13:28,816 --> 00:13:50,335
Occasionally we get lost in anger and we become angry gods.

69
00:13:51,479 --> 00:13:59,649
And of course occasionally we are bathing in absolute wonderful joy and pleasure.

70
00:14:01,551 --> 00:14:18,751
So these are the worlds that we create within ourselves.

71
00:14:19,356 --> 00:14:28,892
So somehow we have to go beyond these worlds.

72
00:14:30,154 --> 00:14:39,328
And that's what we do whenever we practice vipassana.

73
00:14:39,809 --> 00:14:44,638
Because when we practice vipassana we can see these worlds appearing in front of us.

74
00:14:44,972 --> 00:15:02,889
So that was the knower of the worlds.

75
00:15:05,653 --> 00:15:14,000
The next is translates literally as a coachman driving an ox or a horse.

76
00:15:14,403 --> 00:15:35,600
It translates better as an incomparable trainer of trainees.

77
00:15:36,019 --> 00:15:45,428
Ah, si traduce meglio come un addestratore incomparabile di addestrati, di persone addestrate.

78
00:15:46,470 --> 00:15:51,313
And of course he has left us certain rules and regulations that we can follow.

79
00:15:52,355 --> 00:15:59,642
Ovviamente ci ha lasciato delle regole, delle indicazioni che noi dobbiamo seguire.

80
00:16:00,241 --> 00:16:05,486
So on the negative side there are the five precepts, the eight precepts,

81
00:16:06,360 --> 00:16:17,337
and on the negative side there are the five and eight precepts.

82
00:16:19,221 --> 00:16:30,259
And then, of course, for the monastic life, all the rules of the Vinaya.

83
00:16:30,981 --> 00:16:36,110
And on the positive side, he's given us the ten perfections.

84
00:16:37,913 --> 00:16:45,726
And the four Brahma-viharas, the four great illimitables.

85
00:16:50,413 --> 00:16:54,441
Love, compassion, joy and equanimity.

86
00:16:55,028 --> 00:17:14,673
The next one is, he is a teacher of gods and men.

87
00:17:15,498 --> 00:17:19,304
Gods and human beings.

88
00:17:19,765 --> 00:17:26,095
Ah, esseri umani.

89
00:17:27,396 --> 00:17:37,673
So this of course refers to the Dharma, all the teachings of the Dharma.

90
00:17:39,036 --> 00:17:42,500
And of course the practice of vipassana,

91
00:17:43,071 --> 00:18:05,568
of all the absorption techniques, and of course how to live the spiritual life in ordinary daily life.

92
00:18:07,557 --> 00:18:12,503
And number eight is buddho, which is the one who knows.

93
00:18:15,028 --> 00:18:36,078
So this is simply saying that he knows how we create the world of samsara, the world of ongoing.

94
00:18:37,897 --> 00:19:06,875
and the escape so remember he said he only taught two things dukkha and the end of dukkha and dukkha is all the miseries that you can think of

95
00:19:07,919 --> 00:19:13,926
And then the final quality is bhagavā, which means exalted, sublime.

96
00:19:13,987 --> 00:19:37,436
Yes, it's an honorific, like we say of the Dalai Lama, his holiness.

97
00:19:38,647 --> 00:19:52,684
So those nine qualities he has accomplished and has destroyed all his defilements.

98
00:19:58,131 --> 00:20:03,778
He was self-awakened.

99
00:20:04,213 --> 00:20:10,803
He has a clear understanding of our situation and because of that virtuous conduct.

100
00:20:18,492 --> 00:20:21,998
He has completed the journey and he did it skillfully.

101
00:20:22,038 --> 00:20:33,073
He knows all the worlds that we can create and how to get out of them.

102
00:20:33,863 --> 00:20:43,916
He's a wonderful trainer, a coach.

103
00:20:51,147 --> 00:20:52,009
Life coach.

104
00:20:54,772 --> 00:21:00,681
And he's also a great teacher.

105
00:21:01,977 --> 00:21:08,384
He has penetrated the human condition, he is the Buddha.

106
00:21:08,565 --> 00:21:26,787
And therefore we consider him to be exalted, sublime and blessed.

107
00:21:26,969 --> 00:21:43,068
I hope my words have been of some assistance.

108
00:21:44,490 --> 00:21:55,525
That's this silly Google Assistant.

109
00:21:56,517 --> 00:22:08,612
A very great annoyance.

110
00:22:10,094 --> 00:22:21,428
So, I hope my words have been of some assistance.

111
00:22:21,969 --> 00:22:24,751
That I have not caused confusion.

112
00:22:25,288 --> 00:22:30,215
Spero di non avere contribuito a confusione, invece.

113
00:22:30,236 --> 00:22:33,519
And that by your devotion to the past, you will be liberated.

114
00:22:34,480 --> 00:22:40,670
E che grazie alla vostra devozione nei confronti del cammino, voi possiate essere liberati.

115
00:22:41,711 --> 00:22:44,034
Sooner rather than later.

116
00:22:44,795 --> 00:22:49,221
Prima piuttosto che più tardi, che più in avanti nel tempo.

